element_texts.text:
Sabbath __ Maple Grove Aug.  1860
My dear good husband:
I have just retired to my chamber for a few minutes ___ with
you.  It has beena beautiful day.
We have had a glorious sunset & soon,
twilight will let her curtain down, & pin
it with a star;" so of course I can 
say only a few words at this time.
I attended church this P.M. for the 
first time. & Listened to a very good ser-
mon from a minister from Montegue,
I forget his name. It seemed very
much as it did three years ago. It would
seem so perhaps, if I had sit in
the gallery with the choir. It did
one a great deal of good, to see how
glad they all appeared to see me.
It didn't seem at all as though I 
had been away so long a time as three 
years. All the faces were quite familiar

to me excepting some of the childrens
They said I looked natural, only I 
was much thiner than I used to be.
Many of my old friends inquired particularly after
your health, if you came with me, and if you
were going to cum for me etc. I left Eddie
asleep, but James Tyler staid at home
to amuse him, & Chandler & Aunt Wright
staid with Mother, so they could see
that he did no mischief. Eddie loves
James very much, + would like to be
with him all the time.  He wanted to
go home with him after church, but I
thought it wasn't best. I am going
over there this week sometime when we
come home from church. James came out
to meet us, drawing Eddie + Eva both in
Eva's little carriage.  They all seemed very 
happy indeed.  Eddie seemed nearly well
today. His bowels have moved but once.
I have noticed no symptoms of the Ague
about him yet. I have taken quinine twice
+ shall have to take more tomorrow.

As you think you have the dumb Ague?
I hope not.   How have you been
spending the sabbath? You have taken
a ride of course, & have you attended 
church? Does our nice home look
gloomy, without mama & Eddie?  I 
have thought about you a great deal
today & almost wished the time had 
arrived for me to return.  I enjoy being 
at home very much indeed, but there 
is such a sadness connected with it 
it takes the pleasure off in a measure
Mother has suffered more than usual
to-day. The excitement of yesterday oc-
casioned it I presume, [Mrs. Allen &] Aunt 
Wright came back yesterday, + Mrs. Allen 
came with her, + my Aunt from
Northfield cam to bring them, Emily was
here too, + we had callers beside.  Mother
enjoys having her children near her &
enjoys conversing with them, when she is
not to tired, but other company, + so much
talking annoys her very much I think.

Chandlers little girl is quite unwell with 
diarrhea. she is bout though.  Eddie 
calls mama, and its quite dark so I 
will go + perhaps say a few words this 
Evening, good bye -- Evening:  I 
thought I would ___ some this evening
but its late + I feel a little tired, +
after reading in the bible I guess I shall
feel like going to bed. Now let us exchange
good loving kisses -- May our good
Father watch over + protect you through the night
+ each coming night + day. good night-
my good noble husband.
Monday evening - I have been quite
busy all day + am feeling rather tired to-
night. Eddie seems quite well now + enjoys 
playing around here very much.  He think
everything of Jennie & James Lylia(?). I really
believe he is forgetting is papa + Jesse, and all
the folks there, he has said nothing about
Lammar for several days. Tis all"Toz'n" (Cousins) now
with him, He and Eva get along nicely together now.
Bet he is wide awake I'll assure you -

I don't know as I shall be able to get 
me a Bay State Shawl, for I have given 
up the idea of visiting any where but here, 
unless I stop on my way home at Chisapa(?) 
+ make a short visit at my Aunts -

Eddie is just at the right age to be 

troublesome, + I shouldn't enjoy visiting 
with him among strangers or relations 
either. + I prefer staying with Mother 
while I remain.  It is getting so 
cool I shall have to get some thick-
er clothes for Eddie. + I hardly know 
what to get. The folks here think I 
had better not pants on him this 
winter. They say his is to young + to 
small. I must decide upon something 
soon.  Aunt Wright is here yet 
+ we enjoy to have her here very much. 
Chandlers little girl has been quite 
unwell with bowel complaint, but is 
a little better. but I am getting 
so sleepy I can hardly see to write. 
The folks send much love to you and Charles
